</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Congenital variants and anomalies of the aortic arch are important to recognize as they may be associated with vascular rings, congenital heart disease, and chromosomal abnormalities, and can have important implications for prognosis and management. The purpose of this article is to review cross-sectional imaging techniques used in the evaluation of the aortic arch, describe the embryology and anatomy of the aortic arch system, discuss aortic arch variants and anomalies, and review other malformations of the aortic arch, including interrupted aortic arch, hypoplastic aortic arch, and aortic coarctation. Aortic arch variants and anomalies will be reviewed in the context of a theoretical double aortic arch system. Arch anomalies can be associated with symptoms, such as dysphagia lusoria in the setting of left aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery. Arch variants that form a vascular ring, such as double aortic arch, can result in respiratory distress due to tracheal compression. Certain arch anomalies are strongly associated with congenital heart disease, including right aortic arch with mirror image branching. Other malformations of the aortic arch have important associations, such as type B interrupted aortic arch, which is associated with a locus 22q11.2 microdeletion. Noninvasive imaging at CT angiography and MR angiography allows for comprehensive evaluation of the aortic arch and branch vessels in relation to surrounding structures. Familiarity with the spectrum and imaging appearances of aortic arch variants, anomalies, and malformations is essential for accurate diagnosis and classification and to guide management.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160033">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160033">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig1.jpeg" height="2627" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Schematic figure depicting development of the embryonic aortic arches and branches. Six pairs of primitive aortic arches develop between the ventral and dorsal aortae. Gray areas represent segments that normally involute.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig2.jpeg" height="1699" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Schematic depicting a hypothetical double aortic arch system with bilateral aortic arches and bilateral ductus arteriosi. The primitive fourth embryologic arches contribute to the aortic arches and arch vessels, along with portions of the dorsal aortae (all shown in red). The primitive sixth embryologic arches contribute to the ductus arteriosi and central pulmonary arteries (blue).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig3a.jpeg" height="866" width="643" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Coronal oblique minimum intensity projection CT images demonstrating arch sidedness. <b>(a)</b> Left-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the left main-stem bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Right-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the right main-stem bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Double aortic arch with both right-sided (red arrow) and left-sided (blue arrow) aortic arches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig3b.jpeg" height="866" width="599" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Coronal oblique minimum intensity projection CT images demonstrating arch sidedness. <b>(a)</b> Left-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the left main-stem bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Right-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the right main-stem bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Double aortic arch with both right-sided (red arrow) and left-sided (blue arrow) aortic arches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig3c.jpeg" height="866" width="611" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Coronal oblique minimum intensity projection CT images demonstrating arch sidedness. <b>(a)</b> Left-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the left main-stem bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Right-sided aortic arch (arrow), which crosses the right main-stem bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Double aortic arch with both right-sided (red arrow) and left-sided (blue arrow) aortic arches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig4.jpeg" height="1726" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Schematic depicting a normal left aortic arch on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. The normal left aortic arch results from regression of the right arch between the right subclavian artery and the descending aorta, including the right ductus arteriosus (gray). The first branch arising from the arch is the right brachiocephalic artery, followed by the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig5.jpeg" height="1069" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Normal left aortic arch in a 17-year-old boy. Sagittal oblique four-dimensional flow MR image demonstrates a normal left-sided aortic arch with conventional arch branching pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig6.jpeg" height="1720" width="1592" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Figure depicting left aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery without diverticulum of Kommerell on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. This anomaly results from regression of the right arch between the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries, including the right ductus arteriosus (gray). The first branch arising from the arch is the right common carotid artery, followed by the left common carotid artery, left subclavian artery, and finally the aberrant right subclavian artery, in that order.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig7a.jpeg" height="695" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Left aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery in a 13-year-old boy with McCune-Albright syndrome (same patient as in Movie 1). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the left-sided aortic arch (blue arrow), and the aberrant right subclavian artery passing posterior to the esophagus. Note the absence of a diverticulum of Kommerell at the origin of the aberrant right subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CT image shows the aberrant right subclavian artery posterior to the esophagus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig7b.jpeg" height="695" width="585" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Left aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery in a 13-year-old boy with McCune-Albright syndrome (same patient as in Movie 1). <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the left-sided aortic arch (blue arrow), and the aberrant right subclavian artery passing posterior to the esophagus. Note the absence of a diverticulum of Kommerell at the origin of the aberrant right subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique maximum intensity projection CT image shows the aberrant right subclavian artery posterior to the esophagus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig8.jpeg" height="1622" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Figure depicting right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery arising from a retroesophageal diverticulum of Kommerell on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. This anomaly results from regression of the left arch between the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries (gray), usually with persistence of the left sixth arch as the ductus arteriosus or ligamentum arteriosum (dashed lines), which completes the vascular ring. The first branch arising from the arch is the left common carotid artery, followed by the right common carotid artery, right subclavian artery, and finally the aberrant left subclavian artery, in that order. Both the aberrant left subclavian artery and the ductus arteriosus or ligamentum arteriosum arise from a retroesophageal diverticulum (of Kommerell), which is a remnant of a dorsal left fourth arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig9a.jpeg" height="1460" width="1342" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch, and the left common carotid artery as the first branch to arise from the arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image (posterior to <b>a</b>) shows the aberrant left subclavian artery as the last arch branch, arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from below shows a vascular ring surrounding the trachea and esophagus. <i>ETT</i> = endotracheal tube, <i>NG</i> = nasogastric. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch vessels and the likely position of the left ligamentum arteriosum, coursing between the left pulmonary artery and the apex of the diverticulum of Kommerell that gives rise to the aberrant left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig9b.jpeg" height="1460" width="1110" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch, and the left common carotid artery as the first branch to arise from the arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image (posterior to <b>a</b>) shows the aberrant left subclavian artery as the last arch branch, arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from below shows a vascular ring surrounding the trachea and esophagus. <i>ETT</i> = endotracheal tube, <i>NG</i> = nasogastric. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch vessels and the likely position of the left ligamentum arteriosum, coursing between the left pulmonary artery and the apex of the diverticulum of Kommerell that gives rise to the aberrant left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig9c.jpeg" height="1418" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch, and the left common carotid artery as the first branch to arise from the arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image (posterior to <b>a</b>) shows the aberrant left subclavian artery as the last arch branch, arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from below shows a vascular ring surrounding the trachea and esophagus. <i>ETT</i> = endotracheal tube, <i>NG</i> = nasogastric. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch vessels and the likely position of the left ligamentum arteriosum, coursing between the left pulmonary artery and the apex of the diverticulum of Kommerell that gives rise to the aberrant left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig9d.jpeg" height="1418" width="1795" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch, and the left common carotid artery as the first branch to arise from the arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image (posterior to <b>a</b>) shows the aberrant left subclavian artery as the last arch branch, arising from a diverticulum of Kommerell. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from below shows a vascular ring surrounding the trachea and esophagus. <i>ETT</i> = endotracheal tube, <i>NG</i> = nasogastric. <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch vessels and the likely position of the left ligamentum arteriosum, coursing between the left pulmonary artery and the apex of the diverticulum of Kommerell that gives rise to the aberrant left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig10.jpeg" height="1735" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Figure depicting right aortic arch with mirror image branching on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. This anomaly results from regression of the left arch between the right subclavian artery and the descending aorta. Typically, the right sixth arch regresses, with persistence of the left sixth arch as a ductus arteriosus or ligamentum arteriosum (dashed lines), adjacent to the left subclavian artery and connecting the anteriorly positioned left brachiocephalic artery and the left pulmonary artery. The first branch arising from the arch is the left brachiocephalic artery, followed by the right common carotid and then the right subclavian arteries.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig11a.jpeg" height="839" width="808" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Right aortic arch with mirror-image branching in a 35-year-old woman with a history of truncus arteriosus repair (same patient as in Movie 2). <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph demonstrates the presence of a right ventricle–to–pulmonary artery conduit that has calcified, an implantable loop recorder, and a right-sided aortic arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch and branch vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig11b.jpeg" height="840" width="967" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Right aortic arch with mirror-image branching in a 35-year-old woman with a history of truncus arteriosus repair (same patient as in Movie 2). <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph demonstrates the presence of a right ventricle–to–pulmonary artery conduit that has calcified, an implantable loop recorder, and a right-sided aortic arch. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the right-sided aortic arch and branch vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig12.jpeg" height="1590" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Figure depicting right aortic arch with isolation of the left subclavian artery. This anomaly results from regression of the left arch at two segments, both between the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries, and also distal to the left ductus and left subclavian artery. The first branch to arise from this right-sided aortic arch is the left common carotid, followed by the right common carotid and the right subclavian arteries, in that order. The left subclavian artery is not attached to either the aortic arch or the left common carotid artery, but instead connects to the pulmonary artery via a ductus arteriosus that may be patent or closed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig13a.jpeg" height="773" width="674" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Right aortic arch with left descending aorta (circumflex aorta) and aberrant left subclavian artery in a 1-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch itself crossing the midline. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT multiplanar reconstruction shows the arch crossing the midline posterior to the esophagus and trachea. The first branch arising from the arch is the left common carotid artery, followed by the right common carotid artery, right subclavian artery, and finally the aberrant left subclavian artery, which arises from a small diverticulum after the aortic arch has crossed the midline to the left. A left ligamentum arteriosum is also usually present arising from the aortic diverticulum, which completes the vascular ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig13b.jpeg" height="773" width="801" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Right aortic arch with left descending aorta (circumflex aorta) and aberrant left subclavian artery in a 1-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the arch itself crossing the midline. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT multiplanar reconstruction shows the arch crossing the midline posterior to the esophagus and trachea. The first branch arising from the arch is the left common carotid artery, followed by the right common carotid artery, right subclavian artery, and finally the aberrant left subclavian artery, which arises from a small diverticulum after the aortic arch has crossed the midline to the left. A left ligamentum arteriosum is also usually present arising from the aortic diverticulum, which completes the vascular ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig14.jpeg" height="1635" width="1591" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Figure depicting a double aortic arch. This anomaly results from lack of regression of the hypothetical embryologic double arch system. Bilateral common carotid and subclavian arteries arise symmetrically from the bilateral arches. Typically the right arch is larger and higher than the left. Usually only one of the sixth arches persists as a ductus arteriosus or ligamentum arteriosum, most commonly on the left (dashed lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig15a.jpeg" height="862" width="1198" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Double aortic arch in a 2-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a double aortic arch, with a larger and higher right arch and a smaller left arch. <b>(b)</b> Posterior oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows focal narrowing of the smaller left arch, distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery <i>(SCA)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from above shows a symmetric appearance of the bilateral common carotid <i>(CCA)</i> and subclavian <i>(SCA)</i> arteries just above the arches, in keeping with the four-artery sign. The double aortic arch system completely encircles the trachea and esophagus (which are not shown). <i>RCCA</i> = right common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig15b.jpeg" height="861" width="1160" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Double aortic arch in a 2-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a double aortic arch, with a larger and higher right arch and a smaller left arch. <b>(b)</b> Posterior oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows focal narrowing of the smaller left arch, distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery <i>(SCA)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from above shows a symmetric appearance of the bilateral common carotid <i>(CCA)</i> and subclavian <i>(SCA)</i> arteries just above the arches, in keeping with the four-artery sign. The double aortic arch system completely encircles the trachea and esophagus (which are not shown). <i>RCCA</i> = right common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig15c.jpeg" height="859" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Double aortic arch in a 2-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a double aortic arch, with a larger and higher right arch and a smaller left arch. <b>(b)</b> Posterior oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows focal narrowing of the smaller left arch, distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery <i>(SCA)</i>. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image as viewed from above shows a symmetric appearance of the bilateral common carotid <i>(CCA)</i> and subclavian <i>(SCA)</i> arteries just above the arches, in keeping with the four-artery sign. The double aortic arch system completely encircles the trachea and esophagus (which are not shown). <i>RCCA</i> = right common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig16.jpeg" height="1655" width="1578" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Schematic depicting a persistent left fifth aortic arch on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. This anomaly results from development and lack of normal degeneration of a primitive fifth arch, which is located inferior or caudal to the fourth arch.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig17a.jpeg" height="1455" width="1098" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Persistent left fifth aortic arch with both systemic and pulmonary connections in a 1-day-old girl. Complex associated intracardiac defects in this case included double-outlet right ventricle and a large atrioventricular septal defect (not shown). <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a superior left fourth arch, inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), and left pulmonary artery in relation to the left main bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the relationship of the superior left fourth arch and the inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), which both connect the ascending and descending aorta (systemic-to-systemic connection of the fifth arch), giving the appearance of a double-barreled arch. All arch vessels (right brachiocephalic, left common carotid, and left subclavian arteries) arise from the superior left fourth arch. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows a right-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the base of the right subclavian artery to the right pulmonary artery, and a left-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the left fifth arch to the left pulmonary artery (systemic-to-pulmonary connection of the fifth arch).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig17b.jpeg" height="1457" width="1348" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Persistent left fifth aortic arch with both systemic and pulmonary connections in a 1-day-old girl. Complex associated intracardiac defects in this case included double-outlet right ventricle and a large atrioventricular septal defect (not shown). <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a superior left fourth arch, inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), and left pulmonary artery in relation to the left main bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the relationship of the superior left fourth arch and the inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), which both connect the ascending and descending aorta (systemic-to-systemic connection of the fifth arch), giving the appearance of a double-barreled arch. All arch vessels (right brachiocephalic, left common carotid, and left subclavian arteries) arise from the superior left fourth arch. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows a right-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the base of the right subclavian artery to the right pulmonary artery, and a left-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the left fifth arch to the left pulmonary artery (systemic-to-pulmonary connection of the fifth arch).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig17c.jpeg" height="1457" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Persistent left fifth aortic arch with both systemic and pulmonary connections in a 1-day-old girl. Complex associated intracardiac defects in this case included double-outlet right ventricle and a large atrioventricular septal defect (not shown). <b>(a)</b> Coronal MIP CT angiographic image shows a superior left fourth arch, inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), and left pulmonary artery in relation to the left main bronchus. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows the relationship of the superior left fourth arch and the inferior left fifth arch (teal arrow), which both connect the ascending and descending aorta (systemic-to-systemic connection of the fifth arch), giving the appearance of a double-barreled arch. All arch vessels (right brachiocephalic, left common carotid, and left subclavian arteries) arise from the superior left fourth arch. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows a right-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the base of the right subclavian artery to the right pulmonary artery, and a left-sided <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> connecting the left fifth arch to the left pulmonary artery (systemic-to-pulmonary connection of the fifth arch).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig18.jpeg" height="1631" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Figure depicting type A <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. Type A <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> results from arch interruption distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery (gray and black lines). The descending aorta is perfused via a <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig19a.jpeg" height="1472" width="1427" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Type A <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> in a 5-day-old boy. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r59" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r59">59</a>.) <b>(a)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows that the left aortic arch is interrupted distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiographic image shows a large <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr>, which supplies the descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig19b.jpeg" height="1472" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Type A <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> in a 5-day-old boy. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r59" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r59">59</a>.) <b>(a)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows that the left aortic arch is interrupted distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiographic image shows a large <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr>, which supplies the descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig20.jpeg" height="1518" width="1589" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Figure depicting type B <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. Type B <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> results from arch interruption between the origins of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries (gray and black lines). The left subclavian artery and the descending aorta are perfused via a <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig21a.jpeg" height="1511" width="1409" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Type B <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> in an 8-day-old boy with DiGeorge syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiographic image shows that the left aortic arch is interrupted between the origins of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries (red arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows a <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> that supplies the descending aorta. The left subclavian artery arises from the descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig21b.jpeg" height="1511" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Type B <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> in an 8-day-old boy with DiGeorge syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiographic image shows that the left aortic arch is interrupted between the origins of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries (red arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows a <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr> that supplies the descending aorta. The left subclavian artery arises from the descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig22.jpeg" height="1680" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Schematic depicting type C <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system. Type C <abbr title="interrupted aortic arch">IAA</abbr> results from arch interruption proximal to the origin of the left common carotid artery (gray and black lines). The left common carotid artery, left subclavian artery, and descending aorta are perfused via a <abbr title="patent ductus arteriosus">PDA</abbr>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig23a.jpeg" height="1683" width="1444" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Hypoplastic left-sided aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery in a 21-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows that the arch is hypoplastic. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the hypoplastic arch, which gives rise to an aberrant right subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig23b.jpeg" height="1683" width="1205" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Hypoplastic left-sided aortic arch with aberrant right subclavian artery in a 21-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows that the arch is hypoplastic. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the hypoplastic arch, which gives rise to an aberrant right subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig24.jpeg" height="1495" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Schematic depicting aortic coarctation on the basis of a hypothetical double aortic arch system.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig25a.jpeg" height="1012" width="620" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Aortic coarctation and bicuspid aortic valve in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique MR angiographic image shows aortic coarctation (blue arrow) distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery, mild arch hypoplasia, and multiple prominent intercostal collateral arteries. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique magnitude phase-contrast image shows a bicuspid aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig25b.jpeg" height="1012" width="705" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Aortic coarctation and bicuspid aortic valve in an 8-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique MR angiographic image shows aortic coarctation (blue arrow) distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery, mild arch hypoplasia, and multiple prominent intercostal collateral arteries. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique magnitude phase-contrast image shows a bicuspid aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160033/asset/images/large/rg.2017160033.fig26.jpeg" height="885" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Pseudocoarctation in a 23-year-old man. Sagittal oblique volume-rendered CT angiographic image shows buckling and elongation of the descending thoracic aorta without a discrete focal stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160033&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gould SW, Rigsby CK, Donne